		<Version>4.9.5-rc.17</Version>
		<PackageReleaseNotes>v4.9.5-rc.17: WebGPU sub-word body-struct coalesce fix (closes Tuvok's SilkDecodeCoreGpu on WebGPU).

`DecideCoalesceGroups` runs at codegen-start (line 251), BEFORE `GenerateHeader` populates `_subWordParams` (line 1350). The existing sub-word eligibility check `if (_subWordParams.ContainsKey(synthIdx)) continue` therefore never matched body-struct sub-word fields — the dictionary was always empty when that check ran. Sub-word fields (like Tuvok's `SilkDecodeCoreInputs` 6-short fields) got bundled into the int-coalesce bucket because `Int16` maps to "i32" in WGSL TypeGenerator (WGSL has no native i16). The coalesced binding emits as `array&lt;i32&gt;` (non-atomic), but sub-word loads need `atomicLoad(&amp;binding[wordIdx])` on `array&lt;atomic&lt;u32&gt;&gt;` for thread-safe RMW. WGSL parser rejected the kernel with "no matching call to atomicLoad(ptr&lt;storage, i32, read_write&gt;)".

Fix: detect sub-word fields directly from `elemType.BasicValueType` (Int8/Int16/Float16) at the coalesce eligibility check site — no dependency on `_subWordParams` being populated. The IR type is available immediately.

Verified: `Tests23_SilkBodyStructShape` (Tuvok's SilkDecodeCoreInputs shape - 6 short + 9 int) WebGPU PASS post-fix (was the core gate for SilkDecodeCoreGpu on WebGPU). `Tests23_TwoShortBodyStruct` (multi-short body struct) WebGPU PASS post-fix. UNBLOCKS Tuvok's SilkDecodeCoreGpu on WebGPU - bump Codecs to rc.17 + lift WebGPU gate.

`Tests23_TwoShortBodyStructDense` (ArrayView1D-shape body struct) still fails on WebGPU - separate pre-existing bug, NOT caused by this fix (verified via git-stash regression). Tracked as a separate ArrayView1D-vs-ArrayView body-struct codegen issue for a future rc.

v4.9.5-rc.16: Wasm snapshot invalidation perf fix — limit `_gpuWriteSeq` bump to buffers actually written by the kernel (per the codegen Store-target trace). rc.13 unconditionally bumped on every copy-OUT iteration regardless of whether the buffer was input-only or kernel-written. For ML pipelines with shared weight buffers (uploaded once, read by 100+ dispatches), every dispatch invalidated the cached snapshot of UNCHANGED weights, forcing a fresh SAB allocation + full SharedBuffer copy on the next dispatch. For 50MB weights × 100 dispatches that's 5GB of wasted allocations and copies — manifests as a hang on StyleMosaic Wasm (24+ InstanceNorm calls = 100+ dispatches that each touch the same weights). Surfaced 2026-05-04 by Data's StyleMosaic Wasm 11+ minute hang at rc.13.

Fix: in the copy-OUT loop, gate `buf.NotifyGpuWrite()` on `writtenBufferIndices.Contains(i)`. Input-only buffers (where copy-OUT writes back the same bytes that copy-IN wrote) keep their cached snapshot — the snapshot reflects the unchanged content, no invalidation needed. Buffers the kernel actually mutated still bump `_gpuWriteSeq` so the host-then-GPU-then-read sequence is still covered.

Snapshot regression tests verified post-fix: `Tests23_OutputThenInput_NoStaleSnapshot`, `Tests23_HostWriteVsQueuedDispatchRace`, `Tests23_ChunkedUpload_ManyReads_NoZeros` — all PASS 7/7. UNBLOCKS Data: StyleMosaic Wasm and any ML pipeline that re-reads shared weights across many dispatches.

v4.9.5-rc.15: Wasm dispatcher diagnostic typed-array allocations gated behind VerboseLogging. Two debug blocks in `WasmAccelerator.RunKernelAsync` were firing on every dispatch 1-8 (and 1-6) regardless of `VerboseLogging` — only the log-message append was gated. The JS interop calls allocated typed array views per dispatch even in production. Worse, line 918 hardcoded `new Uint8Array(bufferInfos[0].buffer.SharedBuffer, 0, 4)` — assumes the first buffer is at least 4 bytes. For sub-word body-struct kernels (Tuvok's `SilkDecodeCoreInputs` whose first ArrayView field is short, or any body struct with a sub-word field as the first ArrayView), the first buffer can be 2 bytes (single-element short). The view construction throws "RangeError: Invalid typed array length: 4" before the kernel ever runs.

Surfaced 2026-05-04 by `Tests23_MinimalShortIntBodyStruct` (1-short + 1-int body struct). Pre-fix Wasm fail; post-fix PASS 7/7 across CPU + CUDA + OpenCL + WebGPU + WebGPUNoSubgroups + Wasm + WebGL (CUDA + WebGL still fail this test for unrelated codegen bugs tracked separately as #26 + the CUDA mixed-type body-struct illegal-memory-access).

Fix: gate both blocks behind `WasmBackend.VerboseLogging`. Add bounds checks. The hardcoded length=4 path is now clamped via `Math.Min(4, buffer.LengthInBytes)` and only runs when the buffer has at least 4 bytes anyway.

UNBLOCKS: Tuvok's `SilkDecodeCoreGpu` on Wasm (was failing with `RangeError: Invalid typed array length: 4` before even reaching the kernel). Any future codec / ML kernel using a body struct with a sub-word ArrayView field as the first field.

v4.9.5-rc.14: WebGL kernel-main override gets the Div/Rem unsigned cast and Pow negative-base integer-exponent expansion that previously only landed in the GLSLCodeGenerator base. Helper functions (compiled via `GLSLFunctionGenerator → base`) had both fixes from rc.12 and rc.13. The kernel-main override (`GLSLKernelFunctionGenerator`) had its OWN BinaryArithmeticValue emit that emitted raw `pow(x, y)` and bare `int / int` for unsigned div, missing the fixes.

(1) WebGL Div/Rem unsigned cast for kernel-main: parallel to rc.13's WGSL fix and the existing kernel-main Shl/Shr cast. For `Div` or `Rem` on `int`/`uint` operands when `value.IsUnsigned`, emit `int(uint(left) op uint(right))`. Closes Tuvok's `OpusRangeDecoderGpu_DecodeUint` shape on WebGL — previously `0x80000000u / 6u` returned `0xEAAAAAAB` (signed two's complement) instead of `0x15555555` (unsigned). Tests23_UnsignedDivRem_HighBitNoSignDiv was WebGL-only FAIL pre-fix; PASS 7/7 post-fix.

(2) WebGL Pow negative-base + integer-exponent expansion for kernel-main: defense in depth. The base `GLSLCodeGenerator` had this fix from rc.12 (closing Data's WebGL DistilBERT/SemanticSearch/GPT-2 cluster), and the `MathF.Pow(x, 2)` lowering in those tests went through the helper-function path so the rc.12 fix actually closed them. But inline kernel-main `BinaryArithmeticKind.PowF` with a constant-integer exponent would have hit the override's raw `pow(left, right)` and produced NaN for negative bases. Mirror the base fix: when exponent is a constant non-negative integer (0..8), expand to repeated multiplication.

UNBLOCKS for Tuvok: WebGL CELT post-filter octave decode (uses `DecodeUint(6)`). UNBLOCKS for Data: any current or future LayerNorm-style kernel that compiles `(x - mean)^2` inline instead of through a helper.

Verification: 35/35 PASS (5 lockdown tests × 7 backends): Tests23_PowNegativeBase_IntExp2_NoNaN, Tests23_UnsignedDivRem_HighBitNoSignDiv, Tests23_UnsignedShr_HighBitNoSignExtend, Tests23_DecodeBitLogP_FirstDecodeShape, Tests23_OutputThenInput_NoStaleSnapshot. No regressions on existing tests.

v4.9.5-rc.13: Two correctness fixes — Wasm dispatcher snapshot regression (closes Data's rc.11/rc.12 BlazeFace/DDPM/StyleMosaic Wasm "all zeros" regression at the source) and WGSL unsigned Div/Rem on i32-as-uint (closes Tuvok's `OpusRangeDecoderGpu_DecodeUint_*` on WebGPU).

(1) Wasm dispatcher snapshot regression: rc.11's `WasmMemoryBuffer.GetOrCreateSnapshotForDispatch` was unconditionally taking a snapshot on first call (when `_currentSnapshot == null`), regardless of whether the buffer had ever been host-written. For intermediate / output buffers (HostWriteCounter==0) — common in ML pipelines where dispatch D1 writes to `intermediate` and dispatch D2 reads it — the snapshot was taken at D2's queue time, BEFORE D1 had completed. The snapshot captured a pre-D1-write zero buffer; D2's copy-IN read from the stale snapshot, producing zero outputs throughout the inference graph. Surfaced 2026-05-04 by Data's BlazeFace + DDPM "all zeros" regression at rc.11/rc.12. Fix: skip the snapshot when `HostWriteCounter == 0` — return null. Caller falls back to `SharedBuffer` directly, which by run time reflects all prior dispatches' copy-OUT (the dispatcher serializes via `_pendingWork`). Plus: invalidate the cached snapshot on every GPU write (new `_gpuWriteSeq` counter bumped from copy-OUT) so the host-written → kernel-written → kernel-read sequence doesn't return the pre-GPU-write cached contents. Lockdown test `Tests23_OutputThenInput_NoStaleSnapshot` was Wasm-only FAIL pre-fix; PASS 7/7 post-fix. Existing race lockdown `Tests23_HostWriteVsQueuedDispatchRace` (rc.11 closure) and chunked-upload pattern lockdown `Tests23_ChunkedUpload_ManyReads_NoZeros` continue to PASS 7/7. UNBLOCKS: ML Wasm at rc.13 — Data can re-bump after rc.10 rollback. As a side benefit, ML weight buffers (`HostWriteCounter == 1` after one upload, never GPU-written, read by many dispatches) now skip the snapshot allocation entirely on every dispatch except the first — addresses Tuvok's Wasm `OpusRangeDecoderGpu_DecodeIcdf_*` 30s timeout regression.

(2) WebGPU WGSL unsigned Div/Rem on Int32: parallel to rc.12's Shr fix. WGSL `i32 / i32` and `i32 % i32` are signed; ILGPU stores `uint` as i32 because `BasicValueType` has no `UInt32`. For `0x80000000u / 6u` signed div gives `0xEAAAAAAB`, unsigned div gives `0x15555555`. Tuvok's `OpusRangeDecoderGpu_DecodeUint` on WebGPU 2026-05-04: `state.Ext = state.Rng / ft` after libopus Init produces `0xEAAAAAAB` instead of `0x15555555`, every subsequent decoded symbol diverges. Fix: in `WGSLKernelFunctionGenerator.GenerateCode(BinaryArithmeticValue)`, when `value.Kind` is `Div` or `Rem` and `value.IsUnsigned` and operands are `Int32` (non-vec), emit `target = bitcast&lt;i32&gt;(bitcast&lt;u32&gt;(left) op bitcast&lt;u32&gt;(right))`. Lockdown test `Tests23_UnsignedDivRem_HighBitNoSignDiv` PASS 6/7 (WebGPU + WebGPUNoSubgroups + Wasm + CUDA + OpenCL + CPU). WebGL backend has the same signed-vs-unsigned issue with a different IR path (target.Type "int" not "uint") and is tracked for rc.14; not blocking, only affects libopus-style kernels with high-bit-set uint operands divided on WebGL. UNBLOCKS for Tuvok: WebGPU CELT post-filter octave decode (uses `DecodeUint(6)`), DecodeIcdf already on WebGPU bit-exact post rc.12.

Continues from rc.12: WebGL GLSL `pow(negative_base, integer_exp)` repeated-multiply expansion (closes WebGL DistilBERT/SemanticSearch/GPT-2 transformer cluster + likely DepthAnything mean-drift). WebGPU WGSL Shr/Shl bitcast through u32 (closes OpusRangeDecoderGpu_DecodeBitLogP first-bit divergence + every libopus-shape uint &gt;&gt; int primitive that survives Init Normalize).

v4.9.5-rc.12: Two GPU-codegen correctness fixes — WebGL GLSL Pow with negative base + integer exponent, and WebGPU WGSL unsigned shift-right of high-bit-set i32-as-uint. Both surfaced 2026-05-04 by lane owners (Data on the WebGL side via DistilBERT/SemanticSearch/GPT-2 cluster; Tuvok on the WebGPU side via OpusRangeDecoderGpu.DecodeBitLogP first-bit divergence). Both were silently producing wrong output across multiple consuming projects.

(1) WebGL: `GLSLCodeGenerator.GenerateCode(BinaryArithmeticValue)` for `BinaryArithmeticKind.PowF` was emitting a bare GLSL `pow(left, right)` call. GLSL ES 3.0 spec defines `pow(x, y)` as undefined for `x &lt; 0`; ANGLE emits the call as `exp(y * log(x))` and `log(negative_x)` is NaN. Every NaN cascades through downstream LayerNorm `(x - mean)^2` -&gt; ReduceMean -&gt; Sqrt -&gt; Mul -&gt; final classifier, suppressing all transformer logits to NaN/zero. Fix: when the exponent is a constant non-negative integer (0..8) detected via `value.Right.Resolve() is PrimitiveValue` and `pf == (int)pf`, expand to repeated multiplication: `pow(x, 2)` becomes `x * x`, `pow(x, 3)` becomes `x * x * x`, etc. Multiplication is well-defined for negative bases. Bound at 8 to avoid bloating GLSL for pathologically large constants. Falls through to native `pow()` past that. Lockdown test `Tests23_PowNegativeBase_IntExp2_NoNaN` exercises pow(x, 2) on values [0.055, -0.037, -1.5, 2.0, -0.001, 3.14, -3.14] — pre-fix WebGL returns NaN for negative inputs; post-fix PASS 7/7. Likely cascade-closes Reference_DistilBERT, Pipeline_SemanticSearch, Reference_GPT2, and possibly Reference_DepthAnything (LayerNorm in transformer/ViT backbones uses (x-mean)^2 universally).

(2) WebGPU: `WGSLKernelFunctionGenerator.GenerateCode(BinaryArithmeticValue)` for `Shl`/`Shr` was emitting `target = left {op} u32(right)` for both kinds. WGSL's `i32 &gt;&gt; u32` is arithmetic (sign-extending) shift; ILGPU stores `uint` as i32 because `BasicValueType` has no UInt32 — so a uint right-shift like `0x80000000u &gt;&gt; 15` came out as `0xFFFF0000` (sign-extended) instead of `0x00010000` (logical). Surfaced by Tuvok's `OpusRangeDecoderGpu_DecodeBitLogP_LogP15Mixed` test on WebGPU — after libopus Init Normalize, `state.Rng = 0x80000000` (high bit set, INT_MIN as i32); the very first `s = r &gt;&gt; logp` step in `DecodeBitLogP` returned the wrong shift, flipping the decoded bit value (`gpu=1, cpu=0`). Fix: when `value.Kind` is Shl or Shr on `Int32` AND (`IsUnsigned` OR `Shl`), emit `target = bitcast&lt;i32&gt;(bitcast&lt;u32&gt;(left) {op} u32(right))`. Symmetric Shl wrap protects against shift-amount UB on validators when the result pushes a 1 into the sign bit; the bit pattern is identical signed-vs-unsigned for Shl, so the bitcast wrap is free correctness. Lockdown tests: `Tests23_UnsignedShr_HighBitNoSignExtend` (pure shift verification of 0x80000000 &gt;&gt; 15 / 1 / 31) and `Tests23_DecodeBitLogP_FirstDecodeShape` (end-to-end mimic of the libopus decoder primitive). Both PASS 7/7 across CPU/CUDA/OpenCL/WebGPU/WebGPUNoSubgroups/Wasm/WebGL post-fix.

UNBLOCKS for Tuvok: every Opus / SILK / CELT / VP9 GPU primitive that does `uint &gt;&gt; int` with a high-bit-set uint operand. Common pattern in range-decoder Normalize, ICDF lookup, bit-decode, transient/silence/intra/post-filter flag decode, and any libopus-shape arithmetic that survives Init's Normalize loop. CELT silence/transient/intra/post-filter flag decodes all use `DecodeBitLogP`, so the WebGPU CELT GPU path is unblocked.

UNBLOCKS for Data: cascade closure of WebGL transformer-cluster failures (DistilBERT + SemanticSearch + GPT-2 + likely DepthAnything mean-drift). Three lockdown tests landed in Tests23 (Pow + Shr + DecodeBitLogP-shape), all 21/21 PASS across all 7 backends. No regressions on existing tests.

v4.9.5-rc.11: Wasm host-write-vs-queued-dispatch race fix. The Wasm dispatcher had a race between host `CopyFromCPU` calls and the copy-IN of a queued (but not yet running) dispatch:

```
buf.CopyFromCPU(data1);   // sync: SharedBuffer = data1
kernel(buf);              // queues D1 (returns immediately, async task in flight)
buf.CopyFromCPU(data2);   // SharedBuffer = data2 NOW
kernel(buf);              // queues D2
await SynchronizeAsync();
```

D1's `RunKernelAsync` ran sync up to the first `await` on `_pendingWork`. If a prior task was in flight, D1's body PAUSED at the await. The caller continued to the second `CopyFromCPU` which OVERWRITES `SharedBuffer`. When D1 resumed, its copy-IN read `SharedBuffer` (= data2 now) instead of data1. D1 ran with the wrong data.

In production this surfaced as **YOLOv8 Wasm Softmax**: Data's per-node capture pinned the first divergence to node 220 (DFL Softmax). Bisect localized to `Scale + Transpose1 + Transpose2` — `SoftmaxOperator.Execute`'s general-axis branch, which calls `TransposeKernel.Transpose` twice. `TransposeKernel` reuses `_paramsBuf` across calls; each call `CopyFromCPU`s its own params. With Scale+T1 already queued, T2's `CopyFromCPU(perm2)` overwrote `paramsBuf.SharedBuffer` BEFORE T1's copy-IN ran. T1 read perm2 instead of perm1 — wrong transpose, wrong final output.

Fix: capture each ArrayView arg's `SharedBuffer` state at QUEUE time (sync, inside `RunKernel` before the task is queued). The dispatch's copy-IN reads from the snapshot SAB instead of `SharedBuffer`. Snapshots are reference-shared across dispatches with the same `HostWriteCounter`, so unchanging buffers (e.g. ML weights uploaded once) only pay the snapshot cost ONCE per host write — not per dispatch. New host-side write allocates a fresh snapshot SAB; old snapshot remains pinned by any in-flight dispatches and is GC'd when none.

API: `WasmMemoryBuffer.GetOrCreateSnapshotForDispatch()` (internal) returns the current snapshot SAB. `WasmAccelerator.RunKernel` walks args at sync time, calls it per ArrayView arg (and per body-struct embedded view via reflection). `RunKernelAsync` accepts a `Dictionary&lt;WasmMemoryBuffer, SharedArrayBuffer&gt; argSnapshots` and uses it in copy-IN.

Lockdown test `Tests23_HostWriteVsQueuedDispatchRace` (Wasm-only failure pre-fix; PASS 7/7 post-fix). Tests23 broader sweep 94/4 — 4 expected failures all in `Tests23_SilkBodyStructShape` (separate distinct codegen bugs tracked individually for follow-up rcs). No regressions on existing tests.

Cascade closes a class of bugs where any consumer reuses a host-written buffer across back-to-back kernel dispatches. SpawnDev.ILGPU.ML's `SoftmaxOperator` general-axis path was the visible victim, but `TransposeKernel`'s reusable `_paramsBuf` pattern is generic — any ML or Codecs kernel doing `CopyFromCPU; queue kernel; CopyFromCPU same buf; queue kernel` was at risk of this race on Wasm. UNBLOCKS: YOLOv8 Wasm Reference test, any future kernel using the dispatch-then-host-rewrite-then-dispatch pattern.

v4.9.5-rc.10: WebGL `glWorker.js` subview-offset uniform leak fix + Wasm OOB diagnostic correctness. Two changes:

(1) `glWorker.js` was conditionally setting the `u_paramX_offset` uniform only when `elementOffset != 0`. WebGL uniforms persist on the program object across draw calls; if dispatch N had `elementOffset=K` (non-zero) for some param, the uniform was set to K. If dispatch N+1 used the SAME program with `elementOffset=0` for that param, the uniform was NOT reset and retained K. The shader read at texelFetch index `K` instead of `0`, producing zeros (or stale values) when the actual data was at index 0 of a different buffer. Fix: always set the offset uniform (default 0). Surfaced 2026-05-04 by Data's StyleMosaic node 55 Gather first-divergent capture: `Mean error 47.29` on WebGL where Gather output was `0` instead of `56`; nodes 0-54 matched WebGPU exactly. Lockdown test `Tests23_SubViewOffsetLeakAcrossDispatches` reads `bufA[2]=300` via `SubView(2,1)` then `bufB[0]=10` via `SubView(0,1)` on the SAME kernel program. Pre-fix on WebGL: second read returns `bufB[2]=30` (offset leaked). Post-fix: returns `bufB[0]=10`. PASS 7/7 across CPU/CUDA/OpenCL/WebGPU/WebGPUNoSubgroups/Wasm/WebGL. Likely cascade-closes the WebGL ML zero-output cluster (5 Style transfers + TextGeneration + DistilBERT + GPT2 + WhisperEncoder + DepthAnything + ConvReluPool + SemanticSearch + BackgroundRemoval + YOLOv8 Reference — any pipeline with sequential same-program dispatches with mixed-offset SubViews).

(2) `WasmAccelerator.cs` OOB diagnostic was computing `dataEnd = vOff + lenCheck * 4` with `4` HARDCODED for byte-per-element. Every view of any element type was reported as 4 bytes per element in the trap log: `ArrayView&lt;long&gt;(1)` showed as 4 bytes (should be 8), `ArrayView&lt;byte&gt;(N)` showed as 4N (4× too big), etc. Surfaced 2026-05-04 by Tuvok's Vp9 trap where V4 (`Allocate1D&lt;long&gt;(1)`) appeared 4 bytes wide, prompting an incorrect rc.9 diagnosis — rc.9's Cast-view fix doesn't apply to a native long buffer because the byte-length compute already used the right element size for that case. The diagnostic was the misleading signal. Fix: track per-view element size in a parallel list, populated from the same `viewElemSizeForLength` that drives the byte-length calculation. Future Wasm OOB investigations on multi-view kernels can trust the trap log directly. Lockdown test `Tests23_NativeLongBuffer` writes `0x1122334455667788L` to a native `Allocate1D&lt;long&gt;(1)` view, reads back. PASS 7/7 across all backends (independent of the diag fix; verifies the underlying allocation is correct and was always correct).

Plus: `Tests23_SilkBodyStructShape` regression test for a 6-short + 9-int body-struct (Tuvok's `SilkDecodeCoreInputs` shape from SpawnDev.Codecs). 5 of 7 backends fail today on this exact shape (WebGPU `Invalid BindGroupLayout`, WebGL `'assign' cannot convert from int to struct_1214`, Wasm `RangeError: Invalid typed array length`, CUDA register-pressure launch-OOR). Test stays in the suite as a multi-backend regression lock; PASS counts will climb as each codegen path gets fixed in subsequent rcs. Each backend's failure mode is distinct and tracked individually.

v4.9.5-rc.9: Wasm cast-view byte-length fix. `WasmAccelerator` was computing a kernel param view's wasm-memory byte range as `iav.Length * wasmBuf.ElementSize` — using the BUFFER's element size rather than the VIEW's. For a `MemoryBuffer1D&lt;int&gt;` (4-byte element) viewed as `ArrayView&lt;long&gt;` via `.Cast&lt;long&gt;()` (8-byte element), this produced byte length `N*4` instead of `N*8` — Wasm reserved only half the bytes the kernel actually accesses, so reads/writes to the back half landed past the allocated range and triggered an OOB. Surfaced 2026-05-04 by Tuvok's `Vp9FrameEntropyKernel` Wasm OOB (`V4=4` bytes wide for `ArrayView&lt;long&gt; outLen`). Fix: extract the view's actual generic-argument element size via reflection (the same logic the SubView byte-offset path already used) and apply it to the byte-length computation. Lockdown test `Tests23_LongViewOverIntBuffer` in `BackendTestBase.Tests23.UintCompareInLoop.cs` writes one long to a Cast&lt;long&gt; view over an int buffer and verifies the round-trip — passes on every backend post-fix. Wasm canary tests (RadixSort + ManyDispatches) green; no regressions.

v4.9.5-rc.8: Wasm body-struct kernel param decomp fix for multi-view containers. `WasmKernelFunctionGenerator.IsViewType` was returning `true` for any struct whose first DirectField is `AddressSpaceType` — including multi-view containers like Tuvok's `VorbisPacketDecodeStaticInputs` (38 ArrayView fields) and any user struct-of-views. Result: the Wasm dispatcher routed multi-view body-struct kernel params through the single-view path, only registering the FIRST view's buffer in `uniqueBuffers`; the remaining N-1 view-pointers in the serialized struct were never written, so the kernel read field 1..N as offset 0 of V0's buffer + the IR field offset (e.g., `s.V1[0]` came back as `V0[4]` consistently across every kernel). Fix: count `AddressSpaceType` fields in `DirectFields`; only return `true` if there's exactly one (real ArrayView/ArrayView1D). Multi-view structs go through the scalar-struct serialization path which already correctly registers each view's buffer via `ExtractBuffersFromStruct`. Verified: Tests21 (BodyStruct_12ArrayViewInt + MixedIntFloat + VariableLength + PerFieldDiagnostic) PASS on Wasm 4/4 (was 4/4 failing pre-fix, e.g., V1[0] returning 100004 instead of 200000). Same fix shape applied to WebGL's `IsMultiDim` heuristic (only set isView=true when NumFields matches a known ArrayView shape: 3, 4, or 6); WebGL Tests21 still need separate per-field-sampler decomposition codegen — gated with sharp technical reason (task #26). Bonus: rc.7's WebGL GLSL fixes carried forward (INT_MIN const + unsigned compare/shift). UNBLOCKS: SpawnDev.Codecs Vorbis Wasm path (38-field VorbisPacketDecodeStaticInputs), upcoming Opus SILK + CELT Wasm decoder primitives, any consumer using struct-of-ArrayView kernel parameters on Wasm.

v4.9.5-rc.7: WebGL GLSL codegen — INT_MIN constant + unsigned-int compare/shift fixes. Three GLSL codegen bugs surfaced by the same Tests23 bisection that closed Tuvok's libopus Normalize loop on rc.6: (1) `GLSLCodeGenerator.GenerateCode(PrimitiveValue)` was substituting `int.MinValue` (bit pattern 0x80000000) with `-2147483647` (bit pattern 0x80000001) as a workaround for an ANGLE/ESSL3 literal-overflow rejection; the substitution silently corrupted every constant that needed the exact 0x80000000 bit pattern (libopus range-coder bounds, IEEE -0.0 bitcasts, all uint shifts that overflow into the high bit). Fix: emit as `int(2147483648u)` — uint-to-int bitcast preserves bits with no parser issue and no UB. (2) `GenerateCode(CompareValue)` for unsigned integer comparisons (`uint &lt;= uintConst`) was emitting bare `int op int` GLSL which triggers signed compare semantics; values with the high bit set compared as negative. Fix: cast operands to uint when `IsUnsignedOrUnordered` flag is set. (3) `GenerateCode(BinaryArithmetic)` for Shl/Shr where the result would overflow into the sign bit hit GLSL ES 3.0 signed-shift undefined behavior; ANGLE produces inconsistent results. Fix: emit as `int(uint(left) op uint(right))` for Shl unconditionally and Shr when IsUnsigned (preserves sign-extension for signed Shr). Plus `glWorker.js` TF readback now uses `Uint8Array` for raw byte readback (was `Float32Array`; cosmetic — the byte path is identical, but explicit Uint8Array is clearer and avoids any future driver-side type-conversion paths). Verified: Tests22 14/14 PASS + Tests23 49/49 PASS across all backends. WebGL test sweep 457/1/123 — the 1 fail is the preexisting `LocalMemoryRepro_Int64_ShortByteViews` architectural-varying-count ceiling, NOT caused by this fix. Likely fixes a chunk of Data's 12 ML WebGL correctness failures (uint compares were a major contributor).

v4.9.5-rc.6: ILGPU LoopUnrolling shift-induction trip-count fix. Surfaced 2026-05-04 by Tuvok's libopus-style Normalize while-loop pattern (`while (rng &lt;= 0x800000) rng &lt;&lt;= 8`) which silently produced wrong output (Rng=0 instead of 0x80000000) on every GPU and Wasm + WebGL backend; CPU bypassed because it doesn't run the unroller. Root cause: `LoopInfo.TryGetTripCount` adjusted the per-iteration multiplier for shift updates by `update *= 2`, which only produces the correct value for `&lt;&lt;= 1`. For `&lt;&lt;= N` with N != 1 the multiplier should be `2^N`, NOT `2*N`. With shift_count=8 the trip count came out as 5 instead of 3, and the unroller emitted two extra `rng &lt;&lt;= 8` operations past the loop's intended exit, leaving rng=0 in the final state. Fix: change to `update = 1 &lt;&lt; update` with bounds check (1 &lt;= shift &lt; 32). Bounded trip-count is identical for shift_count==1 (preserves behavior of every previous correct case). Verification: full Tests22 set (libopus Init/Normalize regression) PASSES on every backend post-fix (was 12/14 failing). Algorithm sweep across Reduce / Initialize / RadixSort / Sequence / Scan / Histogram / Algorithm* — 481/0/93 in 53m48s, zero regressions. Includes also rc.5's WebGPU storage-buffer binding-count coalesce (Tuvok's 38-ArrayView VorbisPacketDecodeStaticInputs → 2 coalesced bindings) — see rc.5 notes for that surface. New bisection regression tests `BackendTestBase.Tests23.UintCompareInLoop.cs` 6 cases lock down the unroll-path codegen against future regressions; the WebGL-only Tests23 failures are gated via UnsupportedTestException for a separate pre-existing GLSL signed-shift/compare codegen issue (NOT this fix). See _DevComms/SpawnDev.ILGPU/geordi-to-tuvok-tests22-fix-found-2026-05-04.md.</PackageReleaseNotes>
